<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910305-0089</DOCNO><DOCID>910305-0089.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Stephen Swid Drops   His Bid for Nelson   Entertainment Group</HL><DATE>03/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   NNH T.NNH</CO><IN>RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- New York financier Stephen C. Swid hasbacked away from acquiring Nelson Entertainment Group for $30million in cash and notes and $186 million in assumed debt,Nelson and Mr. Swid said.   After negotiations broke down last week, the partiesdecided to allow a letter of intent, signed last December andextended three times, to expire. Nelson, the principaloperating unit of Toronto's NHI Nelson Holdings InternationalLtd., said discussions were continuing with Mr. Swid andother parties about financing or other strategictransactions.</LP><TEXT>   Nelson is a struggling independent film producer anddistributor that holds home video rights to a 900-title filmlibrary, plus home video and foreign rights to films producedby Los Angeles-based Castle Rock Entertainment. Nelson pays75% of the company's production costs.   Mr. Swid couldn't be reached. Individuals close to thesituation said he still wanted to buy the company, but thatthe due diligence process had lowered the proposed price. Mr.Swid reportedly thought the value of Nelson's assets hadfurther eroded with the disappointing theatrical release of&quot;Eve of Destruction&quot; in January, and anxieties about thecoming &quot;The Taking of Beverly Hills,&quot; said to have cost $20million to $25 million.   Critical to determining the future sale of Nelson is theFrench bank, Credit Lyonnais Bank Nederland N.V., a unit ofCredit Lyonnais S.A., which is owed $108 million under acredit facility and another $20 million in secured debtthrough a subsidiary.</TEXT></DOC>